data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In C# 14, new built-in conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` cause the compiler to resolve `array.Contains(item)` to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`Reverse()`** on arrays (resolves to in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). Apply the same fix pattern wherever arrays are used in expression trees with LINQ methods.
